comments.en: This ontology pattern describes geodata types representing core concepts of spatial information (Kuhn 2012) we well as further semantic attribute distinctions relevant for geocomputation and geo-analysis.

comment.en: An attribute of an object line dataset
Point measures are point-like representations of fields. For example, point data sets denoting the locations of measured temperature values.
Intensive region attribute
An attribute whose values are measures in a dataset
The class of reference systems
Boolean attributes are spatial attributes within the range of True/False. They are special types of (bi)nominal attributes
Atrribute of some region data sets
The class of data items. Data items bind together different attributes of an observation, just like table records or primary keys.
The class of domains of reference systems. This is a class of classes of reference systems, which is not expressible in OWL, but in RDF.
A vector representation of a field. Can be a point or line measure, or a coverage
A generalized geometry, including 2D and 3D extended regions. In 2D, this might be a Polygon.
Attribute of some vector data set
Attribute of some point data set
This is a spatial attribute which denotes a bounded phenomenon. Can be either a object vector or an existence raster
This type of lattice has an extensive attribute. For example, a spatial dataset about the population number of municipalities
The class of symbols that refer to observable phenomena and belong to a reference system
The class of data sets (collections of data items)
These levels correspond to Stevensons scale levels and could be extended by further ones.
Field rasters are raster representations of continuous fields. For example, raster layers representing a terrain height (DTM).
Coverages are tessellated layers that represent a continuous field. For example, landuse polygons.
Existence rasters are rasters representing boolean fields (fields denoting whether something is present at a cell location or not).
Attribute of some Line data set
A raster data set is a special kind of tessellation, where regions are regular squares.
Temporal reference systems

comment.undefined: This denotes a list of references, defined over some dataset (using property ofDataSet) and some attribute property of that dataset (using property ofAttr). It is used to talk about value lists as an enity (e.g. a GIS attribute)

comment.en: Object vectors are vector representation of a set of objecs and their quality. For example, a point layer denoting points of Interest (POI) or buildings in a city together with their quality, e.g. the building height.
Spatial attribute on ratio scale level
An attribute that represents the quality of an object (core concept)
An interval scaled attribute
An attribute that denotes counts of discrete entities (compare Chrisman 1998)
The class of attributes whose values are supports of a dataset
Attribute of some Raster
Spatial reference systems
This attribute represents a quality of an event (core concept). For example, the duration.
Object reference systems
Extensive region attribute
A type for a spatial track. A spatial track is a vector representation of "fix" events of some moving object. For example, a GPS track of points of a person moving.
Events represented in terms of an attribute of a vector data set. For example, the magnitude of earthquakes represented as an attribute of a point data set.
A spatial attribute on nominal scale level
This is a vector data set which is tessellated (and no raster)
Contour layers are coverages that denote intervals of the reprepresented continuous field. For example, temperature intervals, represented as regions bounded by isolines of a temperature field.
Linear representations of fields. Examples are isoline maps
A list of values of some attribute in a dataset
Attributes of a tabular dataset. Each attribute corresponds to a column in the table.
A spatial attribute on ordinal scale level
An attribute of an object point dataset

A vector layer attribute that satisfies a boolean expression and thus denotes the 'existence' of some attribute encoded phenomenon across space. Example is a layer of polygons of ''forest'' landuse or a layer of "parks".
A lattice is a spatial tessellation that represents objects and their qualities. For example, a set of municipalities with average income.
Vector data sets are spatial data sets that are not raster
An attribute which represents the quality of a field (core concept). This implies that the spatial data items in this data set are self-similar (their parts have the same attribute)
An attribute of a tesselation data set
Quality reference systems
A generalized notion of a point in 2D and 3D
A generalized notion of a line in 2D and 3D
A region data set where spatial regions are tessellated (jointly covering and mutually non-overlapping) within a spatial extent
A dummy property that realizes a full round to connect an attribute with itself via hasSupport (required to define the attribute subclass SupportAttribute)
Inverse of hasValue
The relation between a data item and its data set

Links value lists to some attribute property. This attribute property links items of the dataset of the value list to their references. Used to define a value list. Note this is not in OWL anymore (ranges over properties)
Dummy property used to self connect attributes via measures, in order to define a MeasureAttribute
Inverse of hasSupport
The relation between an attribute and one of its elements
describes a data reference which is a region (can be measure or support).
This property defines the dataset of a value list. Thereis only one dataset for a value list
Part of relation between references.

This is a special link to a (local) reference system which is actually a collection of classes. For example, class intervals defined for a choropleth map. The references of this system are classes and the reference systemis a class scheme
The relation between a data item and its measure
the inverse of elementOf
The relation between a reference and its reference system. For example, a reference would be 50 and the reference system  may be Celsius
The relation between a reference and its reference system. For example, a reference would be 50 and the reference system  may be Celsius
the inverse of elementOf
the inverse of elementOf
describes a data reference which is a region (can be measure or support).
The relation between a reference and its reference system. For example, a reference would be 50 and the reference system  may be Celsius
Inverse of hasMeasure
The observation window of a data set. This is a (spatio-temporal) reference for which the data set represents a complete (closed world) observation (all facts that are not observed are wrong).
The relation between a reference and its reference system. For example, a reference would be 50 and the reference system  may be Celsius
The relation between a data item and its support
The relation between a reference and its reference system. For example, a reference would be 50 and the reference system  may be Celsius
The relation between a data item and its measure
The relation between a data item and its support
